title: Archos Vision 1 Belt Clip and Headphone Lead Holder

description.text:
I use my Vision 1 to listen to going to work. Normally I pop it into a pocket, feed the lead under my shirt and plug the earphones into my ears.
Then as I walk, my swinging arms catch the lead and pull the 'phones out of my ears. So I designed a simple holder that will hold the Vision, take up the slack and clip it onto my belt. The latter is useful as it keeps access to the player and reduces the stuff I end up putting in my pockets!
The opening for the player is a little on the long side, but suits what i need. Have included the Sketchup file if anyone wants to reduce the height (could probably do with a 2mm reduction).

Arm For printing the arm, I let a thin layer to create for the bearing ball fixing. Just remove it afterward with a cutter blade. Insert the bearing ball (623ZZ: cylindrical type, 3x10x4 mm) and fix it with a screw (M3, with low head). Support part You can screw the motor directly on the support part.
Screw the first 3 screws (M3), then put a spring, place the arm and screw the last screw to maintain all parts together. Screw the PTFE push fit connector directly in the motor support. There are 2 holes (30 mm between holes) to fix the bowden extruder to whatever support (I will post the support to fix the bowden extruder on a reprap) you're ready to print !

Naturally 623ZZ are among those 30 or 35 types I've got now, along with 693ZZ,  603ZZ as close neightbours, and 684ZZ, 694ZZ - one, if not any of those could be alternatively squeezed into a fit, I suppose. title: Cool Birdhouse
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This is a double shell, solar-vented cool birdhouse for the Birdhouse Challenge, printable in one piece. Your chicks will thank you! There is a drain at the bottom and a ring of ventilation holes at the bottom and top of the inner shell, and another ring of slots and holes at the bottom and top of the outer shell. Any sunlight on the outer shell sets up a convection cycle with cooler air being drawn in through the lower ring of slots and rising to exit the large holes, so the inner shell and nest remain cooler. A post and ring joins the two shells at the top for a sturdy hanger. The roof, lack of a perch, and gap between shells makes it difficult for a predator to reach the eggs or chicks. There's no bird bath because chicks won't appreciate the resulting disturbance or encouragement of predators, and the opening is high enough that the chicks won't fall out before they are ready. Please let me know how you do! I used http://www.drsfostersmith.com/pic/article.cfm?aid=2194 as a guide to design. Sizing - check. Heating and cooling - check, but there's no insulation for winter except to cover exterior holes to trap dead air. Proper drainage - check. Safety - check, while there's no metal plate, there are two openings that would have to be enlarged, and a squirrel would have trouble hanging on anyway. Mounting and access - check/fail. There is no cleanout plug - you'll have to use a hooked wire and fish out all the nesting materials to clean it out.

Print in one piece.  Your printer will need to be well tuned.  This was printed in one piece on a Solidoodle 3 with 1.75mm ABS at 205C.  The walls are 1.5mm, recommend 20% infill and 3-4 shells.  The opening (32mm or 1-1/4") can be trimmed for the specific species or the size can be scaled.  Critical points to watch are the base, the mid-level vent slots, and the tops of the inner and outer shells.  If you can't print the base well, you should probably concentrate on getting this right before continuing.  You can see in one of the photos that the top of the inner shell was challenging; I have added some fins to help with closing the inner top (not shown).  
160mm dia x 175mm tall - scale to fit your printer.  
Sunlight can break down plastic over time through UV exposure so be sure to paint it with a light colored water-based non-toxic acrylic spray paint if you want it to last.

This is an update of my Pottery Barn soap dish.  As you can see from the pictures it has been broken several times, but cannot be replaced because it is discontinued.  I\'m trying to make an unbreakable replacement.
I managed to do all of the modeling parametrically this time, so there shouldn\'t be any mesh-related weirdness.

Half is modeled to accomodate the Makerbot's build area.  Print 2 and glue them together with ABS cement from the plumbing aisle.  ABS pipe cement is just acetone with ABS plastic melted in it.  Thin the cement with acetone, and dip the dish to create a smooth surface.  
Alternate between sanding and filling with a brush or dipping to hide the seam and create a smooth surface.  The ABS cement is goopy, and is good for filling.  A thinner solution is better for smoothing.
If you need a color other than black, you can make your own cement.  Use a grinder and your ABS filament to make shavings or powder, and mix it with acetone.
I finished this dish with several coats of sprayed on white plastidip to give it a smooth, slightly rubbery surface.

This is a Rodin coil frame I designed after watching a Marko Rodin seminar. It was modeled after the winding pattern he had on the board. There are numbered grooves in the toroid to hold the wires for an easier time wrapping.It is comprised of 2 channels with the following winding pattern:
A: 1,16,31,10,25,4,19,34,13,28,7,22,1...
B: 2,17,32,11,26,5,20,35,14,29,8,23,2..
it works well with 24 winds per channel
Channels A and B are wound 180* out of phase. So when you finish channel A, start B in the other direction around the core making an X.
When you run it with your function generator, connect the output of A to the input of B. It will levitate spherical magnets while spinning them.
All credit for the coil design goes to Marko Rodin. I know he would like others to take interest in his work, so if this is something you think others will like please feel free to share.
I have started making other designs for testing and may upload them if there is any interest.

title: Christmas tree with balls and star (fits on small printers)

description.text: This is a small DIY Christmas tree with balls and a star, made for small printers such as the 3Dtje mini printer. By printing the two halves diagonally on the printbed, the full height of +/- 12 cm (4.7") can be printed even when the bed is only 10cm x 10cm. The balls should of course be printed multiple times in different colors and for the slightly thicker star gold or silver sounds nice. Have fun printing, best wishes and happy new year!

Notes: I used 100% infill on this, mostly because it was a tiny print (only 2.5 cm tall) and the antenna needed to have the strongest connection to keep it from snapping off. This way, there's no need to fuss with supports and that tricky antenna!
Standard cleaning....adding little eyeballs with superglue I used an exacto knife to clean up any burrs and remove any stringing that occurred.
Printable adapter plate for THK KR26 linear stages. THK sell these separately ($$) as an aluminum part but I thought: "why not design my own?

Printed as-is without support in PLA @ 0.1mm layer height. The captive nut recesses on the bottom of the print have filleted corners so there is minimal bridging required as long as the layer height is kept reasonable. Support may be required if you use thick layers. Infill can be low for most applications.
My application will be fairly light duty (z-axis on a resin printer) so I'm hoping the stepper will stay cool enough for the PLA to hold up. If you know you will be running the motor hard you may want to print in ABS or Nylon as steppers can get pretty toasty.

(4 of each)
  • M3-20mm screws
  • M3-6mm screws (longer may be ok depending on your stepper)
  • M3 nuts

    Assembly

    -Insert the M3 nuts into the plate
    -Place the plate on the face of the motor with the nuts facing the motor (the motor should partially cover the nuts keeping them in place)
    -Screw the plate to the motor using the M3-6mm screws
    -Loosen the flexible coupler on the KR26 and insert the motor shaft into the coupler and bolt the plate/motor assembly to the linear stage using the M3-20mm screws
    -Tighten the flexible coupler

This is the building I live in in Boston (also the building we started my current company wayfair.com in).  Pretty fun to have a mini replica of where you live.   The overhanging deck in the back came out suprisingly good!

I printed this on a Makerbot with an automated build platform. I found that I needed to print it with a raft given the height. Also the standard raft configuration has a gap between the raft lines which I found allowed the building to flex too much in the X direction as it got tall. To remedy this I changed the Base infill density to .65 in skeinforge. This makes the raft lines closer together so that they actually touch and form a raft that is more solid in both the X and Y directions. I left the raft attached.

Board fits well, but I was having some trouble printing in PLA because the corners were lifting from the print bed. Probably just a setting in Slic3r or I need to modify the surface of my print bed. Just used blue painters tape. This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/9YU5IxoXiPk

Pretty simple zprobe mount. I use a micro limit switch without the metal lever - remove it ;) I run a Smoothie board. The zprobe is not intended to run before each print - you run it once and unless you change the bed the plane should be fine. If curious, read http://smoothieware.org/zprobe#toc17 On my mendel max 2 printer there is approx 4mm from the zmin. I was lazy on the endstop mount, its just a 3mm tall rectangle but it should also be easy to use different switches.
